# Tasked — a fast, private, fully client-side To-Do app

A complete task manager that runs as a **single static site** (HTML + CSS + vanilla
JS — no backend, no build step, no framework). **All your data stays on your
device** in the browser's IndexedDB. It works offline, installs as a PWA, and runs
identically on `localhost` and on Namecheap shared hosting — including inside a
subfolder like `example.com/todo/`, because every path is relative.

---

## Files

```
index.html      App shell & markup
style.css       All styling (theming via CSS custom properties)
app.js          All application logic
sw.js           Service worker (offline caching + notifications)
manifest.json   PWA manifest
icons/          icon-192.png, icon-512.png (placeholders — swap for your own)
README.md       This file
```

---

## Run locally

A service worker needs to be served over `http://` (not opened as a `file://`
path), but **`localhost` is exempt from the HTTPS requirement**, so any tiny
static server works:

```bash
# Python 3
python -m http.server 8080

# or Node
npx serve .

# or PHP
php -S localhost:8080
```

Then open **http://localhost:8080/**. That's it — the app seeds a few sample
tasks on first run so you never see a blank screen.

> Opening `index.html` directly from disk (`file://`) will load the UI but the
> service worker, offline caching, and notifications won't register. Use a local
> server for the full experience.

---

## Deploy to Namecheap shared hosting

1. **Upload** the whole folder (or its contents) via cPanel **File Manager** or
   FTP into `public_html` (for the site root) or `public_html/todo/` (for a
   subfolder).
2. **Enable free HTTPS.** In cPanel open **SSL/TLS Status** (AutoSSL) and run
   *Run AutoSSL* for your domain. HTTPS is **required in production** for the
   service worker and notifications to work. (AutoSSL is free on Namecheap.)
3. Visit your URL. Because all paths are relative and the service worker is
   registered with `{ scope: './' }`, it works at both:
   - `https://example.com/`
   - `https://example.com/todo/`

No `.htaccess`, database, or server config is needed.

### Why relative paths matter
Every asset reference (`style.css`, `app.js`, `manifest.json`, `icons/…`), the
manifest's `start_url`/`scope`, and the SW registration are all **relative**
(`./`). That's what lets the app live in a subfolder without rewriting anything.

---

## Icons

`icons/icon-192.png` and `icons/icon-512.png` are simple generated placeholders.
**Drop your own** PNGs at those exact paths/sizes (192×192 and 512×512) to
rebrand — the manifest and service worker already reference them. They're marked
`purpose: "any maskable"`, so use a design with ~10% safe padding for Android
maskable icons.

---

## Data & backups (read this!)

- **Primary store:** IndexedDB (tasks, projects, tags, habits).
- **Small UI prefs** (theme, last layout): `localStorage`.
- The app calls `navigator.storage.persist()` to ask the browser to keep your
  data even under storage pressure, and shows usage via `navigator.storage.estimate()`
  in **Settings → Data & backup**.

Because the data is local, **clearing your browser data / site storage will erase
it.** Protect yourself:

- **Settings → Backup → JSON** for a full one-click backup (and **Import** to
  restore/merge). Do this regularly — the app will nudge you every ~7 days.
- **CSV** export for spreadsheets, **.ics** export for calendar apps.

---

## Reminders — honest limitations

The app uses a **layered, backend-free reminder system**:

1. **In-app alerts** while the app is open — reliable.
2. **On-load catch-up** — every time you open the app it surfaces overdue/missed
   items.
3. **OS notifications** via the Notifications API + service worker — these fire
   **only while the app or browser is running**. Enable them in **Settings**
   (permission is requested on a button press; HTTPS or localhost required).

> ⚠️ **A reminder that fires when the browser is *fully closed* is not reliably
> possible in a no-backend web app.** The Notification Triggers API was
> abandoned, and Web Push requires a server. This app does **not** fake guaranteed
> background reminders.
>
> **For critical deadlines, use the `.ics` export** and add the event to a real
> calendar (Google/Apple/Outlook) — that's the dependable fallback.

Installing as a **PWA** (Add to Home Screen / Install) gives the best possible
notification behavior the platform allows.

---

## Feature overview

- **Quick-add with natural language** — `Submit report next Friday at 3pm every 2 weeks #work !p1`
  parses date, time, recurrence, `#tags`, and `!p1–!p4` priority, and strips them from the title.
- **Views:** List, Today, Upcoming, Kanban board, Calendar (month, drag to
  reschedule), Eisenhower Matrix, Time-block Planner.
- **Tasks:** Markdown notes, 4 priorities, due date+time, separate start/"do"
  date, time estimate, energy tag, subtasks, checklists, colored tags, favorites,
  pins, flags.
- **Organization:** Areas → Projects → Sections, recurring tasks (iCal RRULE via
  rrule.js with human-readable text), Someday, Archive, Trash with Undo.
- **Productivity:** Pomodoro timer (survives refresh), time tracking, habit
  tracker with streaks, gamification (points/levels/streaks + vacation mode),
  stats & charts, focus mode, templates.
- **UX:** Dark/light/warm themes (respects `prefers-color-scheme`), command
  palette (`Ctrl/⌘K`), search (`/`), single-key shortcuts, drag-and-drop
  (SortableJS, touch-friendly), confetti/sound/haptics (off by default),
  reduced-motion support, semantic HTML + ARIA live regions + keyboard nav.
- **PWA & offline:** installable, app-shell precaching, CDN libs runtime-cached.

### Keyboard shortcuts
| Key | Action | Key | Action |
|----|--------|----|--------|
| `N` | New task (focus quick-add) | `Ctrl/⌘K` | Command palette |
| `/` | Search | `Ctrl/⌘Z` | Undo delete |
| `g` then `t/u/i/a` | Go to Today/Upcoming/Inbox/All | `1`–`5` | Switch layout |
| In a task row: `Space` complete · `Enter` open · `Del` delete · `f` flag · `p` pin | | | |

---

## CDN libraries (with local-fallback note)

Loaded from jsDelivr and runtime-cached by the service worker so they keep
working offline after the first online load:

- **chrono-node** — natural-language date parsing (loaded as an ES module via
  jsDelivr's `+esm` bundle, since chrono v2 ships ESM only; `app.js` reads it
  from `window.chrono`)
- **rrule.js** — recurrence rules (classic `<script>`)
- **SortableJS** — drag-and-drop (classic `<script>`)

`app.js` degrades gracefully if a CDN is blocked (the core app still runs; only
NL-date/recurrence/drag conveniences are affected on a first offline load).

**To self-host** (e.g. corporate networks that block CDNs): download each library
into a `./vendor/` folder and update the library tags in `index.html` to point
there (for chrono, change the `import` URL in the `<script type="module">`).
Then they're precached like the rest of the shell.

---

## Privacy

No accounts, no servers, no analytics, no network calls except the three CDN
script loads (which you can self-host). Your tasks never leave your device.
